Data_Dictionary_Transformation()¶

In [2]:
def Data_Dictionary_Transformation(dict_source,First_Cols_Keep,First_Rows_Elim,Feature_Column,df):
    
    #Load Data Dictionary
    Data_Dictionary = pd.read_excel(dict_source,engine='openpyxl',usecols=list(range(First_Cols_Keep)))[:First_Rows_Elim]
    
    #Replace Spaces with Dashes
    Data_Dictionary[Feature_Column] = Data_Dictionary[Feature_Column].apply(lambda x: x.replace(' ','_'))
    
    #Features that are not in the data source
    Bad_Features = [feature for feature in Data_Dictionary[Feature_Column].values.tolist() if feature not in df.columns]

    #Features that are in the data source
    Good_Features = [feature for feature in df.columns if feature not in Data_Dictionary[Feature_Column].values.tolist() + ['Sort','Auto','Home']]

    Bad_To_Good_Dict = {Bad_Feat : Good_Feat for Bad_Feat,Good_Feat in zip(Bad_Features,Good_Features)}
    
    Data_Dictionary[Feature_Column] = Data_Dictionary[Feature_Column].apply(lambda x: Bad_To_Good_Dict[x] if x in Bad_Features else x)
    
    Data_Dictionary = Data_Dictionary.append(pd.DataFrame([[col]+['No Information']*4 for col in [col for col in df.columns.values.tolist() if col not in Data_Dictionary[Feature_Column].values.tolist()]],columns=Data_Dictionary.columns)).reset_index(drop=True).fillna('No Information')
    
    return Data_Dictionary

Join()¶

In [3]:
def Join(TableOne,TableTwo,TableOneJoinKey,TableTwoJoinKey):

    #Set TableTwo's index by TableTwoJoinKey
    TableTwo = TableTwo.set_index(TableTwoJoinKey)

    #Join Operation
    for col in [col for col in TableTwo.columns if col not in [TableTwoJoinKey]]:
        TableOne[col.title()] = TableOne[TableOneJoinKey].apply(lambda x: TableTwo.loc[x][col])
    
    #Return final results where TableOne and Table Two are joined similiar to a SQL JOIN
    return TableOne

FeatureDashboard()¶

In [4]:
def FeatureDashboard(df,Data_Dictionary,DISPLAY,SORT,Sort_Feature,ASC):
    
    #Dashboard Columns
    
    #Missing Obs. within each feature
    nullValues = pd.Series(df.isnull().sum()) 
    
    #Missing Obs. Percentage within each feature
    nullPercentage = pd.Series(round(df.isnull().sum()/df.shape[0],4))
    
    #Unique items within each feature
    uniqueObs = pd.DataFrame([[feature,len(df[feature].unique())] for feature in df.columns]).set_index(0)[1]
    featureDataTypes = pd.Series(df.dtypes,name='Data Type')
    
    #Create Dashboard 
    dashboard = pd.concat([nullValues,nullPercentage,uniqueObs,featureDataTypes],axis=1).reset_index()
    
    #Dashboard Columns
    dashboard.columns = ['index','Missing','Null Percentage','Unique','Data Type']
    
    #Join Current Dashboard with information from the data dictionary to help further analysis
    dashboard = Join(TableOne = dashboard,TableTwo = Data_Dictionary,TableOneJoinKey = 'index',TableTwoJoinKey = 'FIELD NAME').rename({"index" : "Feature"},axis=1)
        
    #Flag for sorting dashboard based on a specific metric
    if SORT == True:
        dashboard = dashboard.sort_values(Sort_Feature,ascending = ASC).reset_index(drop=True)
    
    #Flag for displaying and returning the dashboard
    if DISPLAY == True:
        pd.set_option('display.max_rows', None)
        pd.set_option('display.max_colwidth', None)    
        display(dashboard)
        pd.set_option('display.max_colwidth', 50)
        pd.set_option('display.max_rows', 10)
        return dashboard
    
    #Return final dashboard
    return dashboard

Missing_Features()¶

In [5]:
def Missing_Features(df,missing_threshold=0,drop=False):
    
    #Number of missing features per each observation
    df['Features_Missing'] = df.T.isnull().sum()
    
    #Filter data based off missing feature threshold where the observations above/equal will be filtered and displayed
    df2 = df[df['Features_Missing']>=((df.shape[1]-1)*missing_threshold)]
    display(df2)
    print(f"{df2.shape[0]}/{df.shape[0]} = {(df2.shape[0]/df.shape[0])*100}% of Observations")
    
    #Flag for droping the observations above/equal the threshold and keeping any observations bellow
    if drop == True:
        df = df[df['Features_Missing']<((df.shape[1]-1)*missing_threshold)].reset_index(drop=True).drop('Features_Missing',axis=1)
        return df

Unique_Dashboard()¶

In [6]:
def Unique_Dashboard(df,DISPLAY):
    
    #Data container for final results
    UniqueDashboard = []
    
    #All feature that are categorical in nature
    features = df.dtypes[(df.dtypes==object)|(df.dtypes==bool)].index.tolist()
    
    #For each feature we will find the unique item & proportion of the specific feature
    for feature in features:
        
        #Feature count used to get unique item and count of that item
        ValueCount = df[feature].value_counts()
        
        #Add result to data container
        UniqueDashboard.append([feature] + [[index,round(count/df.shape[0],4)] for index,count in zip(ValueCount.index,ValueCount.tolist())])
    
    #Convert data container into a dataframe
    UniqueDashboard = pd.DataFrame(UniqueDashboard).fillna('-').set_index(0) 
    
    #flag for displaying the dashboard and not returning it
    if DISPLAY == True: 
        pd.set_option('display.max_rows', None)
        pd.set_option('display.max_colwidth', None) 
        pd.set_option('display.max_columns', None)
        display(UniqueDashboard)
        pd.set_option('display.max_colwidth', 50)
        pd.set_option('display.max_rows', 10)
        pd.set_option('display.max_columns', 20)
        
    #Or the dashboard will be returned for future use
    else:
        return UniqueDashboard

findCorrelation()¶

In [7]:
def findCorrelation(newData,excludedFeature):
    
    #Data which has a specific feature excluded
    newData = newData.drop(excludedFeature,axis=1)
    
    #Data container for final results
    corrList = []
    
    #For every Column in corr matrix
    for col in newData.corr().columns:
        
        #For every Row in corr matrix
        for row in range(newData.corr().shape[0]):
            
            #Add results to data container
            corrList.append([col,newData.corr().index[row],newData.corr().iloc[row][col]])
    
    #Convert datacontainer into a dataframe
    corrDF = pd.DataFrame(corrList,columns=['Feature_One','Feature_Two','Correlation']).sort_values('Correlation',ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)
    
    #Filter corrDf to avoid any correlations of 1 (Same feature comparision)
    corrDF = corrDF[corrDF.Correlation != 1].reset_index(drop=True)
    
    #Return Results
    return corrDF

def GeoPandaGraph(shp_file_name,df,df_column,shp_column):
    import geopandas
    
    #Load Shape File
    shp_file = geopandas.read_file(shp_file_name)

    #Counts for location based on metric
    ValueCounts = df[df_column].value_counts()/df.shape[0]

    #Exclude any locations that are not in data
    exclude = [town for town in shp_file[shp_column] if town not in Luke_Data[df_column].unique()]
    
    #Create column for counts created above
    shp_file['Frequency'] = shp_file[shp_column].apply(lambda x: 
                                                       ValueCounts[str(x)] 
                                                       if (x != None) & (x not in exclude)  
                                                       else 0)

    #Create color map for value counts
    from matplotlib.colors import LinearSegmentedColormap
    cmap = LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list(
        'mycmap', [(0, '#2F2E2C'), (1, '#0025FF')])
    
    #Chlorpleth Map for specific area
    ax = shp_file.plot(column='Frequency',figsize=(7, 7), alpha=1, edgecolor='black',cmap=cmap, legend=True)
    
    #Set background to black for style reasons
    ax.set_facecolor('black')
    show()

Sentence()¶

In [9]:
def Sentence(x):
    
    #Remove punc from sentence
    for item in ['?','!',',','.','(',')','/','"']:
        x = str(x).replace(item,"")
    
    #Make sentence lower case and split by whitespace
    x = x.lower().split(" ")
    
    #If the sentence has one word make it null
    if len(x) == 1:
        x = nan
        
    #Set sentnece = 1 if item contains keywords
    else: 
        if len([item for item in x if item in ['remove','drop','delete']]):
            x = 1
        
        #If keywords not present then make sentence null
        else:
            x = nan
            
    #Return x - p.s. making certain rows null will make them eaiser to drop so we can focus on keyword obs.
    return x

Age¶

The current age field is not good enough. There is data to fix this however. By pulling the year from the birth date field, a new and improved age field can be calculated

In [96]:
Jason_Data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(Jason_Data['Birth_Date'])
Jason_Data['year']=Jason_Data['date'].dt.year

Jason_Data["year"].fillna(0, inplace = True)
Jason_Data['year']=Jason_Data['year'].astype(int)

Jason_Data['Age']=2020-Jason_Data['year']
Jason_Data["Age"].replace({2020: np.NaN},inplace = True)

Jason_Data['Age'].fillna((Jason_Data['Age'].median()), inplace=True)

In [104]:
def value_count_dashboard(df,row_count):
    value_count_df = pd.DataFrame()
    
    #how can Nate_features be a global variable?
    df = Nate_Data
    
    categorical_features = df.dtypes[df.dtypes == object].index.tolist()
    for feature in df.dtypes[df.dtypes == object].index.tolist():
        df[feature] = df[feature].fillna('Missing Observation')
        value_count_df = pd.concat([value_count_df,pd.DataFrame([[feature,round(count/df.shape[0],3)] for feature,count in zip(df[feature].value_counts().index,df[feature].value_counts().values)],columns=[feature,f'Precentage of {feature}'])],axis=1)
    if row_count == 'MAX':
        pd.set_option('display.max_columns', None)
    else:
        pd.set_option('display.max_rows', row_count)
    pd.set_option('display.max_rows', None)
    display(value_count_df.fillna('-').T)
    pd.set_option('display.max_columns', 20)
    pd.set_option('display.max_rows', 10)

Visualizations¶

In [108]:
def Viz(df,target,drop_list):
    for feature in df.drop(drop_list,axis=1).columns:

        figure(figsize=(8,8))

        data0 = df[df[target]==0][feature].value_counts()
        data1 = df[df[target]==1][feature].value_counts()


        barh([str(feature) for feature in data0.index],log10(data0.values),label=0)
        barh([str(feature) for feature in data1.index],log10(data1.values),label=1)

        title(f"{feature}: Distinct Frequency (Log10 Scaled) vs. {target}",size=20)
        ylabel('Distinct Feature',size=15)
        xlabel('Feature Frequency (Log10 Scaled)',size=15)
        legend(title=target,title_fontsize=15,prop={"size":20})
        show()

from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
labelEncoder = LabelEncoder()

AAA_Combined_OHE = df.copy()

for column in list(AAA_Combined_OHE.dtypes[(AAA_Combined_OHE.dtypes == object)|(AAA_Combined_OHE.dtypes == bool)].index):
    AAA_Combined_OHE[column] = labelEncoder.fit_transform(AAA_Combined_OHE[column].values)

for the auto dataset¶

  • What I did was I updated the example to FIRST oversample the minority class to have 40 percent the number of examples of the majority class (e.g. 169624 * .40 --> 67,849), then use random undersampling to reduce the number of examples in the majority class to have 40 percent more than the minority class (e.g. about 147,497).

In [132]:
over = SMOTE(sampling_strategy=0.4, k_neighbors= 6)
under = RandomUnderSampler(sampling_strategy=.46)
steps = [('over', over), ('under', under)]
pipeline = Pipeline(steps=steps)
X, y = pipeline.fit_resample(X, y)
